A section of Nairobi Jubilee MCAs have urged former Gatanga MP Peter Kenneth to vie for city governor.The nine city MCAs also urged the Kenya National Congress Party leader to dissolve the outfit and join Jubilee Party."We welcome Kenneth to Nairobi. We believe he has good policies and agenda to transform this great city," Ngara MCA Mwaura Chege said.Kenneth said at a church service in Eastleigh on Sunday that he will not run for president in 2017 but will instead support president Uhuru Kenyatta's re-election.Read: Peter Kenneth sets eyes on race for Nairobi governor, to support Uhuru in 2017 pollThe 2013 presidential candidate also said he is considering running for Nairobi or Muranga governor post in the next year's polls.He did not however state whether he will use the KNC party in 2017 elections or will fold up and join JP.But deputy minority leader Ngaruiya Chege said: "Now that he has declared he will support the president next year, the best thing for him to do now is to fold up his party and join the vehicle that the president will use. " Ngaruiya said they have not endorsed Kenneth for the Nairobi seat but welcomed him because "Jubilee is a democratic party."The MCAs addressed journalists at City Hall on Wednesday.Read: Peter Kenneth will shake up Nairobi, politicians say on governor bid On Sunday, Senator Mike Sonko and nominated MP Johnson Sakaja - both have declared interest in the City's top seat - welcomed Kenneth to the race.Other people who have declared their interest in the seat are former Starehe MP Margaret Wanjiru, Water CS Eugene Wamalwa, former National Assembly Speaker Kenneth Marende, Raila Odinga's former aide Miguna Miguna and Esther Passaris.